03848nam a22005415i 9780773587953DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20122012xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735879537 a10.1515/97807735879532doi  a(DE-B1597)657285  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ1397 ǂb A36 2012eb 7aEDU0160002bisacsh04a500.81 aRayner-Canham, Marelene, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCreating Complicated Lives :bWomen and Science at English-Canadian Universities, 1880-1980 /cMarelene Rayner-Canham, Geoff Rayner-Canham; ed. by Marianne Ainley. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tEditors’ Note -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- tA Complicated Life: My Journey to Feminist Enlightenment -- tNew Horizons: Women and Science in Academe, 1880–1920 -- tAcademic Realities of Single Women, 1920–1980 -- tComplicated Lives I: Family Life and Science, 1920–1950 -- tComplicated Lives II: Family Life and Science after 1950 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy have Canadian women scientists been written out of the historical record? Who were they? What did they accomplish? What were their life paths? These are some of the questions answered in this authoritative work. Over decades of research, Marianne Ainley identified, tracked down, and interviewed surviving scientists. Creating Complicated Lives weaves the lives and work of these pioneers with the author's own experiences as an immigrant scientific technician and later a feminist historian. Ainley argues that we must look at the lives of women scientists through a new historical lens that takes into account both the advances of science and concurrent debates about the advancement of women. Rather than having linear career trajectories, many women shifted fields, coped with discrimination, and endeavoured to find niches in which they could make significant contributions. Never before has there been a survey of the lives and work of early Canadian women scientists. This nuanced study brings their stories to light, comparing, contrasting, and interpreting their very complicated lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSex discrimination in sciencezCanadaxHistory. 0aWomen in higher educationzCanadaxHistory. 0aWomen in sciencezCanadaxHistory. 0aWomen scientistszCanadavBiography. 0aWomen scientistszCanadaxHistory. 7aEDUCATION / History.2bisacsh1 aAinley, Marianne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPrentice, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRayner-Canham, Geoff, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358795340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773587953423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773587953/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles